Walk, Dont Run is a comedy film set in Tokyo during the Olympic Games in 1964. The movie marked the last appearance by Cary Grant in a feature film and also the final film of director Charles Walters.

Sir William Rutland - Bill - arrives in Tokyo a couple days early before the fortnight of the Olympic Games of 1964. With no hotel rooms available anywhere, Bill pulls a notice card from the British Embassys bulletin board, and then he talks his way into subletting a room in Christine Eastons apartment. Soon, Bill encounters Steve Davis, an architecture student who also has no room for the night, and so he sublets part of her apartment to Davis. Bill next tries to play matchmaker to the younger pair.
